  "eprint": {
    "title": "Tailored Limb Counts, Faster Arithmetic: Improved TMVP Decompositions for Curve5453 and Curve6071",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Murat Cenk",
        "email": "gamzeorhon@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "N. Gamze Orhon Kılıç",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Halil Kemal Taşkın",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Oğuz Yayla",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Curve5453 and Curve6071 are Montgomery curves over the primes $2^{545}-3$ and $2^{607}-1$, providing 271- and 302-bit classical security, respectively.\r\nTheir TMVP-based field multiplication in 10-limb representation costs 77 multiplications.\r\nWe reduce this to 60 for Curve5453 ($22\\%$ fewer) using a 9-limb radix-$2^{61}$ representation, and to 54 for Curve6071 ($30\\%$ fewer) using a 12-limb radix-$2^{51}$ representation with hierarchical block-level TMVP.\r\nChoosing the limb count to produce $3 \\times 3$ Toeplitz blocks aligns the structure with the size-3 TMVP formula, computing each block product in 6 multiplications rather than 9.\r\nPortable C implementations benchmarked on ARM64 and x86-64 confirm speedups of up to $16\\%$ in field multiplication and $13\\%$ in scalar multiplication.\r\nOn ARM64, Curve5453 reaches $90.6\\%$ of OpenSSL's assembly-optimized NIST P-521 ECDH throughput with 12 additional bits of classical security, and Curve6071 delivers 302-bit classical security at $80.8\\%$ of P-521's throughput.",
    "keywords": [
      "TMVP",
      "Field multiplication",
      "Montgomery curves",
      "Radix representations",
      "Efficient implementation"
    ],
    "category": "Public-key cryptography",
    "publication_info": "Preprint.",
